# FEMA GO Platform Enhancement  
**UX Lead | Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA)**

![Case Study Cover](assets/case-study-cover.png)

## Overview

Led UX design for FEMA GO platform modernization after inheriting an existing USWDS-based design system. The work focused on evolving that foundation into a scalable, governed component system for emergency management workflows while improving usability, accessibility, and maintainability across complex grant interfaces.

## Problem

The platform faced several systemic challenges:

- Inconsistent UI and component usage across workflows  
- Fragmented form patterns and validation behaviors  
- Limited scalability of the inherited design system  
- High cognitive load for users completing complex grant applications  
- Accessibility gaps in form interactions and feedback states  

## Constraints

- Existing USWDS foundation with partial implementation  
- Multi-contractor environment with inconsistent standards  
- High compliance requirements, including Section 508  
- Complex, multi-step grant workflows with structured data dependencies  
- Continuous delivery environment with evolving requirements  

## Approach

- Implemented atomic design methodology to standardize component hierarchy  
- Defined reusable UI patterns for forms, alerts, inputs, and actions  
- Established consistent validation and feedback states across workflows  
- Aligned typography, color, and layout systems with accessibility standards  
- Introduced governance through documented component usage and behaviors  
- Conducted recurring usability testing cycles to validate improvements  

## Key Contributions

- Standardized form components, including inputs, dropdowns, and validation states  
- Defined alert and status patterns for success, warning, error, and informational messages  
- Established button hierarchy and interaction states  
- Built consistent layout and card-based content structures  
- Improved modal workflows for inline task completion, including adding equipment  
- Aligned the design system with real application use cases  

## Artifacts

### 1. Alerts and status patterns
![Alerts and status patterns](assets/alerts-and-status-patterns.png)

Standardized visual treatment for success, warning, error, and informational states, including both standard and slim variants.

### 2. Typography scale
![Typography scale](assets/typography-scale.png)

Defined a Public Sans-based type system aligned with USWDS to support readability, hierarchy, and consistency across the platform.

### 3. Card layouts and grid structure
![Card layouts and grid structure](assets/card-layouts-and-grid-structure.png)

Documented reusable card patterns and grid spacing to support scalable layout decisions across structured content views.

### 4. Button states and hierarchy
![Button states and hierarchy](assets/button-states-and-hierarchy.png)

Established primary, positive, and negative actions with consistent hover, focus, active, and disabled states.

### 5. Color theme palette
![Color theme palette](assets/color-theme-palette.png)

Defined the platform color palette, usage guidance, and hierarchy to support accessibility and consistent interaction cues.

### 6. UX design process
![UX design process](assets/ux-design-process.png)

Documented the UI/UX process connecting discovery, research, prototyping, iteration, and delivery to development.

### 7. Grant request details workflow
![Grant request details workflow](assets/grant-request-details-workflow.png)

Applied the design system to a real grant application workflow, including structured request information, navigation, and inline task management.

### 8. Add equipment modal
![Add equipment modal](assets/add-equipment-modal.png)

Designed modal-based interaction for adding equipment within the grant request flow while preserving task continuity.

### 9. Grant request details screen
![Grant request details screen](assets/grant-request-details-screen.png)

Refined the request details screen to improve clarity, section hierarchy, and interaction flow.

## Impact

- Improved consistency across FEMA GO platform interfaces  
- Reduced variation in form behavior and user interaction patterns  
- Increased accessibility compliance through standardized components  
- Enabled faster development through reusable patterns  
- Reduced cognitive load for users completing complex grant workflows  

## Tools and Methods

- Figma  
- USWDS  
- Component-based design  
- Usability testing  
- Design documentation and governance  

## Notes

This repository documents system-level UX leadership focused on scalable design patterns, structured content, and alignment between design and engineering in a high-stakes federal environment.
